immersed in visual culture, such a history seems insubstantial, imprecise, and even, perhaps, unscientific. Documenting the World is about the material and social life of photographs and film made in the scientific quest to document the world. Drawing on scholars from the fields of art history, visual anthropology, and science and technology studies, the chapters in this book explore how this documentation—from the initial recording of images, to their acquisition and storage, to their circulation—has altered our lives, our ways of knowing, our social and economic relationships, and even our surroundings. Far beyond mere illustration, photography and film have become an integral, transformative part of the world they seek to show us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPhotographyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxHistory. 0aPhotographyxScientific applicationsxHistory. 0aPhotographyxScientific applications. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aarchive.  adocument.  afilm.  aphotography.1 aBlaschke, Estelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeimer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Faye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlamm, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitman, Gregg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitman, Gregg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTucker, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVertesi, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilder, Kelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato